{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508663"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:08:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:08:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11348"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11348"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.61,0.11,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3993"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46242"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"3993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/3993"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31162"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4345"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7491"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46242"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERita is a 32-year-old woman who has presented at 28 weeks\u2019 gestation with her first pregnancy (G1P0). The pregnancy has been going smoothly and she has attended all her antenatal appointments. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is rhesus negative and has been reading online about some \u201cinjections\u201d that she needs because of this. She is very nervous about her blood group negatively affecting the baby and she wants some counselling around it.  Repeated blood group and antibody screen reveals that she is O- type, Anti-D antibody \u003Cstrong\u003Enot\u003C/strong\u003E detected. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a correct statement to tell Rita?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["She should have already had an anti-D injection by now","The dose is 625IU every time","She is due for an anti-D injection today","She should get an anti-D injection regardless of her antibodies","If her partner is rhesus negative on 1st testing, she does not need anti-D"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnti-D (rhesus immunoglobulin) is given to all rhesus negative women who do not have preformed anti-D antibodies. A blood test at the booking visit is done to confirm the woman\u2019s blood group and if she has any antibodies (such as anti-D). Current guideline recommends repeating blood group and antibody screen prior to receiving routine Anti-D injection. If a woman has \u003Cstrong\u003Epre-formed anti-D antibodies she should not receive the anti-D injection\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERoutine administration of anti-D during pregnancy includes 625IU at \u003Cstrong\u003E28 and 34 weeks of gestation\u003C/strong\u003E. As well as another 625IU postpartum if the baby is rhesus positive. However, other doses may be required if there are sensitising events (eg. miscarriage, CVS, abdominal trauma, external cephalic version, etc). 250IU is given for sensitising events in the first trimester and 625IU for sensitising events beyond the first trimester. This should be ideally given \u0026lt;72 hours of the event. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe dose is not always 625IU.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf she has had no sensitising events, and repeated blood test reveals that she does not have anti-D antibody, she is \u003Cstrong\u003Edue for her first anti-D injection today\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf a woman is rhesus negative, it is recommended that she receive the anti-D injections \u003Cstrong\u003Edespite the partner\u0027s RhD status\u003C/strong\u003E.  This is because the male might have a weak expression of RhD and may still carry a risk.  It is possible to have 2 tests on 2 separate occasions to confirm the RhD type but is not commonly done and requires further counselling with the parents on the risks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-D immunoglobulin should be given to all women who are rhesus negative after any sensitising event and routinely at 28 and 34 weeks","If a women has preformed anti-D antibodies it is not recommended that she receive the anti-D injections"],"references":["The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. \u0022Guidelines for the use of Rh(D) Immunoglobulin (Anti-D) in obstetrics\u0022. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. 2019. Viewed on November 2022. Accessed via: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Anti-D-guidelines_July-2021.pdf","SA Maternal, Neonatal \u0026 Gynaecology Community of Practice 2020. Anti-D Prophylaxis. The Government of South Australia: SA Health. Access at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/1d9012804ee1d743ac48add150ce4f37/anti%2Bd%2Bprophylaxis_29042016.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-1d9012804ee1d743ac48add150ce4f37-nGzK28o."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31162"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11348"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31162"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-31T14:24:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-31T14:24:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3993"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id"